    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0007"/>
        		<head>Jim Mc Connell to Mlle. Marcelle Guerin,  Saturday 5.30 P.M.<date value="1915-02-27">Feb 27th ‘15</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline>Saturday 5.30 P.M.<lb/>
            <date value="1915-02-27">Feb 27th ‘15</date>
            </dateline>
        		
            <salute>
            Dear Miss Guerin:
            </salute></opener>
        			
        		<p>	
            I would
            feel very much better
            if I could go to see
            you this evening and
            talk with you.  Not
            that any advice I 
            could give would be
            of value, but it
            always helps when one
            realizes that one has
            others on their side,
            
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0009" n="[p.2]"/>
            
            and sympathetic in
            understanding.  You
            seemed so worried and
            so unlike your usual
            self confident self as
            you went out the 
            door this afternoon, and
            your lack of assurance
            made me feel as if
            you needed all kinds 
            of help.  It seems so
            absurd for me to be
            right here and during
            
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0008" n="[p.3]"/>
            
            this time to be of 
            no service to one in 
            whom I am so deeply 
            interested.  I know you 
            well enough to understand
            how well you can manage,
            but I’ve had a weight
            on my soul ever since
            you left me, for I
            noticed you drooped a
            little and seemed sad.
            That shouldn’t be&mdash;
            you’re too fine and
            
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0010" n="[p.4]"/>
            
            altogether too wonderful
            to have all this trouble
            come to you.  Especially
            at this time when you’re
            giving yourself so nobly
            to this work here.
            You’ll remember, won’t you,
            that if there is any way in which I can
            be of use to you
            that you’ll make me
            happy by calling on me.
        		</p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <salute>Yours</salute>
            
            <signed>Jim Mc Connell</signed>
        		</closer>
        		
